Across the three nontrivial cutoffs the hit fraction varies by a factor of $1.4$. The result is stable under reasonable variations of the lower cutoff.

\subsection{Interpretation}

The hit fractions reported above are conditional frequencies under specific Monte Carlo constructions over an explicitly chosen family of toy null models. They are not p-values, do not constitute hypothesis tests against any physical null, and should not be interpreted as evidence against chance in any objective sense. They characterize the observation's numerical behavior within the constructions we built; we draw no further inferential conclusion from them.

\section{Caveats and non-claims}
\label{sec:notclaims}

For clarity: we have not derived $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework; all input masses were known when the comparison was made; and we propose no mechanism. The Monte Carlo characterization of Section~\ref{sec:robustness} asks how often the construction produces such a match within a Koide-conditioned toy null, independently of authorial chronology. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders.

\paragraph{Not the only algebraic route to a comparable number.}
Rivero~\cite{Rivero2011} showed independently in 2011 that the quark triple $(s, c, b)$ with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ satisfies a Koide-like relation $Q \approx 2/3$, and that chained Koide conditions (the ``Koide waterfall'') connect lepton and quark sectors algebraically; this construction recovers $m_s$ in the same numerical neighborhood as the Soddy curvature reported here. The two routes are conceptually distinct: Rivero's construction is purely algebraic and chains Koide conditions across triples, whereas the present construction is geometric and operates on a single Koide-saturating triple via the Descartes circle theorem. Independent algebraic and geometric routes landing in the same numerical neighborhood could indicate shared underlying structure; it could equally indicate that lepton-mass combinations near $1$~GeV are not scarce near the strange-quark mass, a consideration that bears on the evidentiary weight assigned to either route individually.

\paragraph{Not a charm or bottom relation.}
$\mathcal{F}$ has units of $\text{MeV}^{1/2}$, so only $\mathcal{F}^2$ carries mass dimension one; comparisons $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \neq 2$ are not unit-invariant. Restricting to the dimensionally consistent comparison, $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx 95$~MeV is well outside both the charm range ($m_c \sim 1.3$~GeV) and the bottom range ($m_b \sim 4.2$~GeV) at any reasonable scale. We restrict the present note to the strange sector.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}

If future work were to establish that the observation is not coincidental, possible interpretations fall into three broad classes. First, the Koide relation may have a geometric origin that has not been recognized, and the Soddy connection may be its geometric content; in that case the present observation extends the same geometric structure into the strange sector via the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. Second, the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ may be the natural matching scale of some flavor mechanism that produces $m_s$ from leptonic input, in which case the observation is a datum that any such mechanism should seek to reproduce. Third, the observation may be a coincidence of the kind that Koide's relation itself might be: an unexplained numerical regularity that nonetheless remains stable as measurements improve. We do not argue for any of the three.

\paragraph{Author's tentative interpretation.}
The Koide relation has held to one part in $10^5$ for over four decades without an accepted derivation, and $\mathcal{F}^2$ now matches $m_s^{\msbar}$ at the natural lepton-sum scale within current lattice precision. In the author's view, regularities of this kind are best understood as shadows of underlying algebraic structure: the Descartes--Soddy construction is a visualization of an algebraic identity, not an explanation for it. The author makes no case for this reading; the three possibilities enumerated above are offered as a neutral map of interpretations. We report the observation in the possibility that, if such an underlying algebraic structure exists and is eventually identified, the present numerical match may serve as an additional constraint to narrow the search for it.

\paragraph{Conclusions.}
We have introduced an ordinary-Descartes reading of the Koide lepton triple, computed the resulting outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$, and reported the post-hoc but prospectively testable numerical relation $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV $\approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ (residual $+0.042$~MeV against $\pm 0.69$~MeV). The observation is stable across four prior choices, eight scale prescriptions, and the non-excluding lower-cutoff choices tested. The lepton-side quantity is essentially stationary at present precision; future improvements to the lattice strange-quark mass will continue to test the relation directly. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or prediction. The result is presented as a precise numerical regularity whose theoretical status, if any, remains open.

\section*{Computational note}

Central values, lattice-input propagation, and the null-model Monte Carlos reported in this paper are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository at commit \texttt{bb8b1ae}~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}. Four-loop $\msbar$ running is performed via CRunDec~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.273$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = 4.183$~GeV. Lepton inputs are PDG~2024 charged-lepton pole masses. Quark inputs are the FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ Table~11 estimate for $m_s$ and PDG~2024 summary-table values for $m_c$ and $m_b$. Total runtime for the full robustness analysis is under five minutes on a laptop.

\begin{acknowledgments}
The author thanks J.~Kocik for the geometric reinterpretation of the Koide relation that motivated this work, and acknowledges A.~Rivero's independent algebraic work~\cite{Rivero2011} on the strange-charm-bottom Koide tuple, which converges with the present geometric route. The author also thanks the lattice QCD community, whose successive improvements to the strange-quark mass determination made the numerical observation reported here testable. Computational infrastructure and institutional support were provided by Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo.
\end{acknowledgments}

