\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution (MeV) \\
\midrule
FLAG lattice $m_s(2~\text{GeV}) = 93.44 \pm 0.68$ & $0.692$ \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & $0.051$ \\
Charm threshold $m_c(m_c) = 1.273 \pm 0.005$~GeV (not used for $2~\text{GeV} \to \mu_\star$ evolution) & $0.000$ \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs 3L) & $0.039$ \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum & $0.695$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
The lattice input dominates by an order of magnitude over all other sources. Decomposing the total variance: the FLAG $m_s(2~\text{GeV})$ input accounts for approximately $99.1\%$, $\alpha_s$ uncertainty for $0.54\%$, four-loop truncation for $0.31\%$, and the lepton-side propagation for $0.02\%$. The lepton side of~(\ref{eq:residual}) is essentially exact at present precision.

One systematic absent from the above decomposition is the QED scheme conversion on the lepton side. Converting the lepton pole masses to $\msbar$ at leading QED order shifts $\mathcal{F}^2$ by approximately $-0.22$~MeV, moving the comparison residual from $+0.042$~MeV to approximately $-0.18$~MeV. The scheme-insensitive band for the residual is approximately $[-0.18,\, +0.04]$~MeV, entirely within $0.3\sigma$ of the dominant lattice uncertainty.

\subsection{Continuous scale sensitivity}

We compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ for $\mu/\mu_\star \in [0.5, 4.0]$ and compare against the constant $\mathcal{F}^2$. The intervals over which $|\mathcal{F}^2 - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)|$ remains within one and two standard deviations of $\sigma_{m_s}(\mu)$ are
\begin{align}
\text{1$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1845,\,1921]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 2.0\%),\\
\text{2$\sigma$ window:} \quad &\mu \in [1808,\,1996]\;\text{MeV} \;\;\approx\;\mu_\star (1 \pm 5.0\%).
\end{align}
The 1$\sigma$ window is narrow (about $\pm 2.0\%$), confirming that the relation is picking out a specific scale. Running $m_s^{\msbar}$ from $2$~GeV to $\mu_\star \approx 1883$~MeV shifts the mass by $+1.63$~MeV ($+1.7\%$), approximately $39$ times larger than the comparison residual; the scale prescription is not cosmetic. Figure~\ref{fig:convergence} shows historical PDG and FLAG determinations of $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV})$ for context.

\begin{figure}[htb]
\centerline{%
\includegraphics[width=12.5cm]{fig_strange_convergence}}
\caption{Historical PDG (squares) and FLAG lattice (diamonds) determinations of $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV})$ from 2010 to 2024, with shaded $\pm\sigma_{m_s}$ bands at each determination. The horizontal green line marks the lepton-derived target $\mathcal{F}^2$ evolved back to $2$~GeV ($\approx 93.50$~MeV), sitting $+0.06$~MeV above the FLAG~2024 central value of $93.44$~MeV. The shaded bands illustrate the central point of the closing paragraph of Section~1: the $1\sigma$ acceptance window has narrowed from $\sim\!\pm5$~MeV in the early 2000s to $\pm0.68$~MeV in FLAG~2024, and the lepton-derived target enters the $1\sigma$ window only with the most recent lattice generation. The observation is not that something obvious was missed; it is that the discriminatory power to notice it has only recently arrived. \emph{This plot is not an independent validation of the relation.} Future updates to PDG and FLAG averages will continue to test the value directly, since the lepton-side quantity is essentially stationary at present precision. Historical data tabulated in \texttt{results/ms\_history.csv} in the accompanying repository~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}.}
\label{fig:convergence}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Alternative scale prescriptions}
\label{sec:scale_alternatives}

We test eight scale prescriptions and compute $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu)$ at each, comparing against $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.1134$~MeV:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prescription & $\mu$ (MeV) & Hit (within $1\sigma$)? \\
\midrule
$\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ (baseline) & $1883.10$ & yes ($+0.06\sigma$) \\
$m_\mu + m_\tau$ & $1882.59$ & yes (trivially equivalent) \\
$m_\tau$ & $1776.93$ & no ($-2.31\sigma$) \\
$2~\text{GeV}$ (conventional reference, not lepton-derived) & $2000.00$ & no ($+2.46\sigma$) \\
$(m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau)/3$ & $\phantom{0}627.70$ & non-perturbative \\
$\sqrt{m_\mu m_\tau}$ & $\phantom{0}433.30$ & non-perturbative \\
$(m_e m_\mu m_\tau)^{1/3}$ & $\phantom{000}45.78$ & non-perturbative \\
$3/(1/m_e + 1/m_\mu + 1/m_\tau)$ (harmonic) & $\phantom{0000}1.53$ & non-perturbative \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Of the four prescriptions in the perturbative regime, only $\sum m_\ell$ and the trivially equivalent $m_\mu + m_\tau$ produce hits. The next-best lepton-derived alternative ($m_\tau$ alone) misses by $-2.31\sigma$, and the conventional reference scale of $2$~GeV misses by $+2.46\sigma$.

\subsection{Tight null-model test}
\label{sec:null_tight}

Sample candidate triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ with $m_3$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^0, 10^4]$~MeV, $m_1$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}]\cdot m_3$, and $m_2$ solved analytically from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$. The sampler oversamples until $10^5$ Koide-valid triples accumulate. Of these, $74{,}515$ are excluded because $\mu_\star^{(i)} < 1$~GeV, leaving $25{,}485$ retained triples. For each valid triple, compute $\mathcal{F}^{(i)}$ and $\mu_\star^{(i)}$, run $m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$ from the FLAG $2$~GeV input, and record a hit if $|\mathcal{F}^{(i)\,2} - m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star^{(i)})| < \sigma_{m_s}(\mu_\star^{(i)})$. Of $25{,}485$ valid triples, $121$ produced hits:
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{tight}} \;=\; 0.4748\%, \qquad
95\%\text{ Clopper--Pearson CI (sampling noise only):}\;[0.394\%,\,0.567\%].
\label{eq:tight_null}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Prior sensitivity}
\label{sec:prior_sensitivity}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prior & Hit fraction & 95\% CI \\
\midrule
A: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^0, 10^4]$~MeV (baseline) & $0.47\%$ & $[0.39,\,0.57]$ \\
B: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10^{-1}, 10^5]$~MeV (wider range) & $0.32\%$ & $[0.26,\,0.39]$ \\
C: log-uniform $m_1/m_3 \in [10^{-4}, 10^{-2}]$ (smaller ratio) & $0.43\%$ & $[0.35,\,0.52]$ \\
D: linear-uniform on $m_3$ and $m_1/m_3$ (stress test) & $0.23\%$ & $[0.20,\,0.27]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
All four priors give hit fractions in $0.23\%$--$0.47\%$, with fold variation $2.04$. No prior raises the hit fraction above $1\%$.

\subsection{Loose null-model test and filter sensitivity}
\label{sec:filter}

Broadening the comparison from $m_s$ alone to $\mathcal{F}^2$ against all five quark species $\{m_u, m_d, m_s, m_c, m_b\}$ (restricted to $n=2$ for dimensional consistency) yields $p_{\text{loose}} = 0.4748\%$, identical to $p_{\text{tight}}$, because $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx 95$~MeV is well outside the charm and bottom ranges at any reasonable scale, and too large for $m_u$ or $m_d$. The breakdown is shown in Table~\ref{tab:loose}.

\begin{table}[htb]
\centering
\caption{Loose null hit counts by quark species over $25{,}485$ valid Koide triples.}
\label{tab:loose}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Quark species & Hit count \\
\midrule
$m_u$ & 0 \\
$m_d$ & 0 \\
$m_s$ & \textbf{121} \\
$m_c$ & 0 \\
$m_b$ & 0 \\
\midrule
\textbf{Total} & 121 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Filter sensitivity across three lower cutoffs:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
$\mu_\text{min}$ & Tight-null hit fraction \\
\midrule
$0.7$~GeV (extrapolated) & $0.41\%$ \\
$1.0$~GeV (baseline) & $0.47\%$ \\
$1.5$~GeV & $0.58\%$ \\
$2.0$~GeV (excludes the observed lepton triple) & $0.00\%$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Across the three nontrivial cutoffs the hit fraction varies by a factor of $1.4$. The result is stable under reasonable variations of the lower cutoff.

\subsection{Interpretation}

The hit fractions reported above are conditional frequencies under specific Monte Carlo constructions over an explicitly chosen family of toy null models. They are not p-values, do not constitute hypothesis tests against any physical null, and should not be interpreted as evidence against chance in any objective sense. They characterize the observation's numerical behavior within the constructions we built; we draw no further inferential conclusion from them.

\section{Caveats and non-claims}
\label{sec:notclaims}

For clarity: we have not derived $\mathcal{F}^2 = m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework; all input masses were known when the comparison was made; and we propose no mechanism. The Monte Carlo characterization of Section~\ref{sec:robustness} asks how often the construction produces such a match within a Koide-conditioned toy null, independently of authorial chronology. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders.

\paragraph{Not the only algebraic route to a comparable number.}
Rivero~\cite{Rivero2011} showed independently in 2011 that the quark triple $(s, c, b)$ with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ satisfies a Koide-like relation $Q \approx 2/3$, and that chained Koide conditions (the ``Koide waterfall'') connect lepton and quark sectors algebraically; this construction recovers $m_s$ in the same numerical neighborhood as the Soddy curvature reported here. The two routes are conceptually distinct: Rivero's construction is purely algebraic and chains Koide conditions across triples, whereas the present construction is geometric and operates on a single Koide-saturating triple via the Descartes circle theorem. Independent algebraic and geometric routes landing in the same numerical neighborhood could indicate shared underlying structure; it could equally indicate that lepton-mass combinations near $1$~GeV are not scarce near the strange-quark mass, a consideration that bears on the evidentiary weight assigned to either route individually.

\paragraph{Not a charm or bottom relation.}
$\mathcal{F}$ has units of $\text{MeV}^{1/2}$, so only $\mathcal{F}^2$ carries mass dimension one; comparisons $\mathcal{F}^n$ for $n \neq 2$ are not unit-invariant. Restricting to the dimensionally consistent comparison, $\mathcal{F}^2 \approx 95$~MeV is well outside both the charm range ($m_c \sim 1.3$~GeV) and the bottom range ($m_b \sim 4.2$~GeV) at any reasonable scale. We restrict the present note to the strange sector.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}

If future work were to establish that the observation is not coincidental, possible interpretations fall into three broad classes. First, the Koide relation may have a geometric origin that has not been recognized, and the Soddy connection may be its geometric content; in that case the present observation extends the same geometric structure into the strange sector via the natural mass scale of the lepton triple. Second, the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ may be the natural matching scale of some flavor mechanism that produces $m_s$ from leptonic input, in which case the observation is a datum that any such mechanism should seek to reproduce. Third, the observation may be a coincidence of the kind that Koide's relation itself might be: an unexplained numerical regularity that nonetheless remains stable as measurements improve. We do not argue for any of the three.

\paragraph{Author's tentative interpretation.}
The Koide relation has held to one part in $10^5$ for over four decades without an accepted derivation, and $\mathcal{F}^2$ now matches $m_s^{\msbar}$ at the natural lepton-sum scale within current lattice precision. In the author's view, regularities of this kind are best understood as shadows of underlying algebraic structure: the Descartes--Soddy construction is a visualization of an algebraic identity, not an explanation for it. The author makes no case for this reading; the three possibilities enumerated above are offered as a neutral map of interpretations. We report the observation in the possibility that, if such an underlying algebraic structure exists and is eventually identified, the present numerical match may serve as an additional constraint to narrow the search for it.

\paragraph{Conclusions.}
We have introduced an ordinary-Descartes reading of the Koide lepton triple, computed the resulting outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F}$, and reported the post-hoc but prospectively testable numerical relation $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV $\approx m_s^{\msbar}(\mu_\star)$ (residual $+0.042$~MeV against $\pm 0.69$~MeV). The observation is stable across four prior choices, eight scale prescriptions, and the non-excluding lower-cutoff choices tested. The lepton-side quantity is essentially stationary at present precision; future improvements to the lattice strange-quark mass will continue to test the relation directly. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or prediction. The result is presented as a precise numerical regularity whose theoretical status, if any, remains open.

\section*{Computational note}

Central values, lattice-input propagation, and the null-model Monte Carlos reported in this paper are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository at commit \texttt{bb8b1ae}~\cite{KoideSoddyCode}. Four-loop $\msbar$ running is performed via CRunDec~\cite{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = 1.273$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = 4.183$~GeV. Lepton inputs are PDG~2024 charged-lepton pole masses. Quark inputs are the FLAG~2024 $N_f = 2{+}1{+}1$ Table~11 estimate for $m_s$ and PDG~2024 summary-table values for $m_c$ and $m_b$. Total runtime for the full robustness analysis is under five minutes on a laptop.

\begin{acknowledgments}
The author thanks J.~Kocik for the geometric reinterpretation of the Koide relation that motivated this work, and acknowledges A.~Rivero's independent algebraic work~\cite{Rivero2011} on the strange-charm-bottom Koide tuple, which converges with the present geometric route. The author also thanks the lattice QCD community, whose successive improvements to the strange-quark mass determination made the numerical observation reported here testable. Computational infrastructure and institutional support were provided by Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo.
\end{acknowledgments}

