\begin{abstract}
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m_\ell)/(\sum \sqrt{m_\ell})^2 = 2/3$ for the charged leptons has held to one part in $10^5$ for over forty years without an accepted derivation. Treating lepton mass square roots as Descartes-circle curvatures, the outer root of the Descartes quadratic equals the closed form $\mathcal{F} = e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ when Koide holds exactly (Proposition~1). Kocik first observed a Descartes-like reading of Koide; our mutually-tangent variant is mathematically distinct but follows the same geometric spirit. We compute $\mathcal{F}$ for the observed lepton triple and note a post-hoc but prospectively testable numerical observation: $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV is close to the strange-quark $\msbar$ mass at the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau$ within current lattice precision (residual $+0.04$~MeV against $\pm 0.69$~MeV, about $+0.06\sigma$). The lepton-side quantity is fixed to better than $0.01\%$; future lattice improvements will sharpen or refute the present numerical agreement. Under a Koide-conditioned null model with a log-uniform prior on triples, the observed match arises in $0.47\%$ of valid samples (95\% CI $[0.39\%,\,0.57\%]$); this is a model-conditional frequency, not a $p$-value. We report scale, input, prior, and filter sensitivities along with the error budget.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The Koide relation~\cite{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
holds for the observed charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$. Using the PDG~2024 values~\cite{PDG2024} ($m_e = 0.5109989$~MeV, $m_\mu = 105.6584$~MeV, $m_\tau = 1776.93 \pm 0.09$~MeV), one computes $Q = 0.666664$. Although the relation is not part of the standard Standard-Model curriculum, it has been the subject of continuous theoretical investigation since 1981, with derivation attempts, extensions to the neutrino and quark sectors, and geometric reinterpretations appearing across the intervening four decades; we cite the Rivero--Gsponer review~\cite{RiveroGsponer2005} as an entry point and~\cite{Foot1994,Sumino2009,RodejohannZhang2011,Rivero2011,Krolikowski2014} as representative further reading. We treat~(\ref{eq:koide}) as an empirical input.

In 2012, Kocik~\cite{Kocik2012} observed that the Koide relation admits a geometric reading in terms of intersecting circles. Specifically, Kocik generalized the Descartes circle formula to circles meeting at a common angle, and showed that Koide's $Q = 2/3$ condition fits naturally within that generalized framework once the fourth curvature is set to zero (a degenerate ``line'' circle). He does not compute the non-trivial fourth curvature, and he does not connect any geometric quantity to a quark mass. The present work takes a different geometric step: we identify $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$ with three of four curvatures of a \emph{mutually tangent} Descartes-Soddy configuration governed by the \emph{ordinary} Descartes circle theorem, and compute the fourth. We then show (Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes}) that under exact Koide the algebraically simple combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ formed from the leptons coincides with the geometrically determined outer Soddy curvature $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$ of that configuration.

This step does not add mathematical complexity to Koide. The inputs remain the same three lepton masses; the algebraic compression is identical; the only new quantity is the fourth curvature that the Descartes configuration already implies. If Kocik's observation is that Koide's $Q = 2/3$ has a geometric home, this paper's observation is that the home has a fourth wall. Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} is the mathematical contribution, motivated by but not contained in~\cite{Kocik2012}.

Cross-sector mass relations of this kind are an established genre in the flavor literature. The golden quark-lepton mass relation~\cite{RiveroGsponer2005}, which connects charged-lepton and down-type quark masses via $m_\tau m_e m_\mu \approx m_b m_d m_s$, and Rivero's strange-charm-bottom Koide tuple~\cite{Rivero2011} both make contact between lepton and quark sectors algebraically. The present observation arrives by a different route --- geometric rather than algebraic, and operating on a single Koide-saturating triple rather than chaining conditions across sectors --- but lands in the same numerical neighborhood. We note this convergence in Section~\ref{sec:notclaims} without assigning it evidentiary weight beyond what Section~\ref{sec:robustness} supports.

The observation reported here is best characterized as a retrodictive conjecture with future falsifiability: all input masses were known when the comparison was made, so the match is post-hoc in the historical sense, but the lepton-side quantity $\mathcal{F}^2$ is fixed to better than $0.01\%$ precision, making every future update to the lattice strange-quark mass a direct test of the relation. We make no theoretical claim. The contribution of this paper is the computation of $\mathcal{F}$ and the disclosure of the resulting numerical match, together with a sensitivity analysis characterizing how sharply the match depends on the input lepton triple, the evaluation scale, the sampling prior, and the perturbative cutoff.

One further observation bears on the timing of this report. The lepton-derived quantity $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV has been computable since the lepton masses were measured with their current precision, which is decades ago. What has changed is the quark side: the $1\sigma$ uncertainty on $m_s^{\msbar}(2~\text{GeV})$ from lattice QCD was of order $5$~MeV in the early 2000s and has narrowed to $\pm 0.68$~MeV in FLAG~2024. The acceptance window used in the null-model tests of Section~\ref{sec:robustness} scales with this uncertainty; at earlier precision levels, $\mathcal{F}^2$ sitting $+0.04$~MeV from the central value would have been unremarkable, submerged within a much wider band. Figure~\ref{fig:convergence} illustrates this directly: the shaded $\pm\sigma_{m_s}(2~\text{GeV})$ band narrows progressively over the plotted period, and the lepton-derived target line enters the $1\sigma$ window only in the most recent determinations. The observation is not that something obvious was overlooked; it is that the discriminatory power to notice it has only recently arrived.

\section{The Koide relation as a Descartes condition}

We summarize the ordinary-Descartes construction used in this paper for completeness and to fix notation. As discussed in Section~1, this construction is distinct from the generalized-angle reading in~\cite{Kocik2012}.

The Descartes circle theorem~\cite{Coxeter1968} states that four mutually tangent circles in the plane, with curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3, k_4$, satisfy
\begin{equation}
(k_1 + k_2 + k_3 + k_4)^2 \;=\; 2\,(k_1^2 + k_2^2 + k_3^2 + k_4^2).
\label{eq:descartes}
\end{equation}
Given three curvatures $k_1, k_2, k_3$, equation~(\ref{eq:descartes}) is a quadratic in $k_4$ with two real solutions
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,\pm} \;=\; (k_1 + k_2 + k_3) \;\pm\; 2\sqrt{k_1 k_2 + k_2 k_3 + k_1 k_3},
\label{eq:soddy}
\end{equation}
corresponding respectively to the inner and outer Soddy circles tangent to the original three. By convention, the larger-curvature solution $k_4^{\,+}$ corresponds to the smaller circle (the inner Soddy circle, nestled in the gap between the original three), and the smaller-curvature solution $k_4^{\,-}$ is conventionally called the ``outer'' Soddy circle. When $k_4^{\,-}$ is negative, it corresponds to a large circle enclosing the original three; when $k_4^{\,-}$ is positive, as is the case for the observed lepton triple ($k_4^{\,-} \approx 9.75~\text{MeV}^{1/2}$), it corresponds instead to a fourth circle externally tangent to the three but smaller than $k_e^{-1}$ in radius. The ``outer'' label refers to the smaller of the two algebraic roots of the Descartes quadratic, not to literal enclosure. The relevant quantity for our purposes is this curvature $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$.

\begin{Proposition}[Koide and the outer Soddy curvature]
\label{prop:koide_descartes}
Identify $k_i \equiv \sqrt{m_i}$ for $i \in \{e, \mu, \tau\}$. Let $e_1 = \sum_i \sqrt{m_i}$, $e_2 = \sum_{i<j} \sqrt{m_i m_j}$, and $p_2 = \sum_i m_i$. The outer Soddy curvature of the Descartes configuration $(k_e, k_\mu, k_\tau)$ is
\begin{equation}
k_4^{\,-} \;=\; e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}.
\label{eq:k4_geometric}
\end{equation}
The algebraically simpler expression
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F} \;\equiv\; e_1 - \sqrt{p_2} \;=\; \big(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\big) - \sqrt{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}
\label{eq:F_alg}
\end{equation}
coincides with $k_4^{\,-}$ if and only if the Koide relation $Q \equiv p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$ holds exactly.
\end{Proposition}

\begin{proof}
The Soddy form follows from solving the quadratic~(\ref{eq:descartes}) for $k_4$ given $k_1, k_2, k_3$, using the identity $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$ to simplify the discriminant; the smaller-curvature root is $k_4^{\,-} = e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2}$. Setting $e_1 - 2\sqrt{e_2} = e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$ yields $4 e_2 = p_2$. Combined with $e_1^2 = p_2 + 2 e_2$, this gives $e_1^2 = p_2 + p_2/2 = (3/2) p_2$, equivalently $p_2/e_1^2 = 2/3$, which is the Koide condition. Conversely, if $Q = 2/3$ then $e_2 = e_1^2/6 = p_2/4$, so $2\sqrt{e_2} = \sqrt{p_2}$ and the two expressions agree.
\end{proof}

Proposition~\ref{prop:koide_descartes} states the precise algebraic content of the standard-Descartes reading: under exact Koide, the dimensionally simple combination $e_1 - \sqrt{p_2}$, formed without reference to circles, is in fact the smaller Descartes-Soddy root of the configuration whose three input curvatures are the lepton mass square roots. The observed leptons satisfy $Q = 0.666664$, so the equality of~(\ref{eq:k4_geometric}) and~(\ref{eq:F_alg}) holds to one part in $10^5$. In what follows we adopt $\mathcal{F}$ to denote the exact outer Soddy curvature $k_4^{\,-}$ for all numerical computations. Figure~\ref{fig:soddy} shows the geometric configuration schematically.

